snippet.textDisplay: It seems to me that the limiting factor is the stress the bat can take before it breaks. I saw that in your vid with wooden bats. If you put a hinge on the part that holds the bat to allow it to swing (like the arms on a hammer mill) you will reduce the stress on the bat handle and allow it  to be swung much faster. All of your stresses would either be tension from centripetal force or simple compression at the point where the ball hits the bat.

snippet.textDisplay: The math, physics, and science that you put out on the channel is great and reminds me of Mr. Wizard.  Going back and watching episodes, you realize Mr. Wizard wasn’t a nice guy.  You are the opposite of that and you are just annoyingly happy.  You also remind me of my Jr. High School Teacher that taught REACH.  It was a class that 8 or so kids that instead of going to our regular classes every day, we would go half in the morning one day and then half in the morning on another day and as we got older, it changed as to the frequency or length.  By 7, 8, and 9th grade we had it substituting one of our classes for it.  Loved that class. Example of what we did: In 3rd grade we all read the Canterbury Tales, just who we wanted to be and tell our story to everyone, but I remembered these words: “ You will memorize the prologue to the Canterbury Tales in Middle English and I promise you, when you become a senior in High-School you will be thankful that you memorized it now.”!  We performed for Colleges, High-Schools and for the local TV.  Anyway, I guess a too happy southern Church goer is better than a 60 year old mechanical engineer who hates kids and got more money than he could ever made in his life and all he had to do is keep it under control for 15 minutes at a time, lol.  He still does a good job though.
